      num: 'Three',
      title: 'The Island of Saints and Scholars',
      content: `<p>On the morning of 18 August 806, the Vikings came to Iona.</p>
<p>The monastery on the island of Iona, off the western coast of Scotland, was one of the most sacred places in the Christian world. It had been founded in 563 by Columba — Colm Cille, the Dove of the Church — an Irish nobleman who had exiled himself for reasons that later tradition would variously describe as penitence, ambition, and the aftermath of a copyright dispute over a manuscript. He had paddled across the Irish Sea in a coracle and landed on this small, wind-scoured island and decided it was far enough from Ireland that he could no longer see his homeland, which was the point. He built a monastery. He and his monks began converting the Picts of Scotland to Christianity.</p>
<p>Two and a half centuries later, the monastery that Columba built was one of the great centres of learning in the Western world. Its scriptorium produced manuscripts of staggering beauty. Its library held works that existed nowhere else in Europe. Its school trained monks who would travel across the continent — to Northumbria, to France, to Germany, to Italy — carrying Latin learning and Christian mission wherever they went. Iona was not a remote outpost. It was a hub. One of the places where the intellectual life of a supposedly dark age actually lived.</p>
<p>The Vikings did not know or care about any of this.</p>
<p>They came in longships, low and fast in the water, materialising out of the dawn mist with the terrifying efficiency of men who had perfected coastal raiding over generations. The monks on watch would have had minutes. The bell would have rung. The community would have run.</p>
<p>Sixty-eight monks were killed on the beach. The sources call the place Martyr's Bay, and the name has stuck for twelve hundred years. The Viking raiders took what they could carry — silver, gold, whatever objects of value the monastery held — and left. The assault was over quickly. It was one raid among hundreds along the coastlines of Britain and Ireland in those years, one more entry in the long Viking ledger of slaughter and plunder.</p>
<p>But the survivors of Iona had something the Vikings had not taken. Had, in fact, specifically saved.</p>
<p>The book had been in production for perhaps a decade. It was a copy of the four Gospels, each page illuminated with a complexity and beauty that no purely functional explanation can account for. The carpet pages — full-page decorative patterns of interlacing geometric forms — are so dense and so precisely executed that modern analysis has found individual elements less than half a millimetre wide, executed with quill on vellum without the aid of magnifying instruments. Some scholars have theorised that the monks worked with magnifying lenses ground from water-filled glass. Others think they simply worked very slowly, very carefully, in conditions that would have required extraordinary discipline of eye and hand.</p>
<p>The Chi-Rho page — a single page depicting the monogram of Christ — contains more interlaced detail than any comparable object in early medieval art. Nested within its spirals, if you look closely enough, are the faces of men and angels, moths and cats, tiny figures that reward patience and punish hurry. One analysis found that a single square inch of the page contained more than one hundred separate interlaced ribbons.</p>
<p>This book is the <em>Book of Kells</em>. It is now in the Long Room at Trinity College Dublin, where approximately a million people visit it each year. It was made, most scholars believe, on Iona, in the decades before the Viking raid. When the Vikings came, the monks took it with them.</p>
<p>They fled south to Kells, in County Meath in Ireland, where a related monastic community offered shelter. The book survived. The tradition survived. The monks who had built the scriptorium on Iona scattered across Ireland and carried their learning with them, and the wave of Irish monasticism that Columba had set in motion continued to roll outward across Europe.</p>
<p>This was the Irish contribution to the supposedly dark centuries, and it was enormous. Ireland had never been part of the Roman Empire — the legions had stopped at the Irish Sea, unwilling to invest in an island that seemed to offer insufficient return. This meant that when the Western Empire collapsed, Ireland had no Roman infrastructure to lose. The monasteries that Patrick and Columba and Brigid established in the fifth and sixth centuries became the primary vehicles of learning on an island that had no cities, no roads, no urban tradition in the Roman sense.</p>
<p>They built what they had. Scriptoria. Libraries. Schools for the training of clergy that became, in effect, universities avant la lettre. The curriculum was the classical curriculum — Latin grammar, rhetoric, arithmetic, music, computation — supplemented by scripture and the church fathers, and supplemented further by a tradition of vernacular Irish learning that preserved pre-Christian mythology and history in forms that have no parallel elsewhere in early medieval Europe. The Irish monks were the most comprehensively literate community in the Western world.</p>
<p>And they moved. This is the part of the story that matters most. Beginning in the late sixth century and accelerating through the seventh and eighth, Irish monks began founding monasteries on the European continent with a systematic energy that amounted, in effect, to a cultural invasion. Columbanus — a different Columba, no relation to Iona's founder — established Luxeuil in Burgundy in 590, Fontaines in 598, and Bobbio in northern Italy in 613. His house rules, stricter than anything the continental church had seen, spread Irish monastic practice across France and Germany. Bobbio became one of the great manuscript collections of the early medieval world, a library whose holdings would later be mined by Renaissance scholars looking for classical texts to rediscover. Some of what Petrarch and his successors would celebrate as newly recovered antiquity had been sitting in an Irish-founded monastery in the Italian Alps for eight centuries.</p>
<p>Gall, a companion of Columbanus, established what would become the Abbey of Saint Gall in modern Switzerland in 613. The Abbey's library, maintained continuously from its founding through the present day, is the oldest monastic library still in existence. It contains manuscripts in Latin, Greek, and Old Irish. It contains astronomical tables, medical treatises, legal codes, and poetry. It contains, in other words, the continuous intellectual life of the supposedly dark centuries, collected and preserved by people who had no idea the age they were living in was supposed to be empty.</p>
<p>On Martyr's Bay on Iona, the sea covers the beach where the sixty-eight monks fell. The monastery was rebuilt after the Viking raids — eventually the community returned, and it persists to this day as a place of Christian community. The grass grows green and salt-wet over the ground where they died.</p>
<p>The book they saved is still alive. You can go to Dublin and look at it.</p>
<p>A culture that was supposed to have gone dark managed, somehow, to produce one of the most beautiful objects ever made by human hands — and managed, further, to carry it through fire and slaughter to safety.</p>
<p>That is not what darkness looks like.</p>`,
